    },
    {
      "id": "cdbc8cfc673ad7470a2ea49c6cf1499a64ce5454",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 00:56:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/8947/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "225c0028b5e9ce0d4f5b4e58a2b06e21587c1ec9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 02:08:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nRemoving the client version check breaks the ability to remove this workaround in the future.  Without this, the server will do swabbing for all clients that do not connect with OBD_CONNECT_MNE_SWAB, and if this flag stops being sent by the client in the future (e.g. 2.7.0 client vs. 2.6.0 server) then the bug will be reintroduced.\n\nThat is why there is a check for _both_ MNE_SWAB missing, and client version < 2.2.55 before doing the extra swabbing, so that when the workaround is removed in 2.7.0 this code will NOT do the extra swabbing.  It only adds the workaround for unpatched 2.2 clients.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2dcc4e92275b0a2a6801f5547f86452d7a635b2c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 04:09:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nindeed. I guess it's NOT an option to fix this problem by restoring obd_connect_data::ocd_version because this is the only way for the clients to know which servers they are connecting. So the only way is to use a paddingX to remember the real version of clients, how do you think?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c57ac8ea5c15139017abd95c8f50fc2727e2161a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 06:26:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNo, using paddingX means that we would be corrupting some other part of the obd_connect_data later on.\n\nThe original code saves mne_swab_client_ver early on before obd_connect_data is overwritten with the server version, so the problem is really on the client.  The client should reset the ocd_version in client_connect_import() before reconnecting.\n\nHowever, we can't change existing clients to do this retroactively, it is enough to set exp_mne_need_swab only the first time the client connects.  The client cannot possibly change versions (i.e. upgrade) but continue to use the same export on the server.\n\nIt should be enough to add another exp_have_mne_swab:1 flag that is set the first time exp_need_mne_swab is set, and then it prevents the flag from being changed on that export again in target_handle_connect():\n\n        if (!export->exp_have_mne_swab) {\n                export->exp_need_mne_swab =\n                        !(data->ocd_connect_flags & OBD_CONNECT_MNE_SWAB) &&\n                        mne_swab_client_ver && !ptlrpc_req_need_swab(req);\n                export->exp_have_mne_swab = 1;\n        }",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "dbac994ba987e9cf6b1b945ff059cfcf693296d3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 16:37:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n{quote}\nHowever, we can't change existing clients to do this retroactively, it is enough to set exp_mne_need_swab only the first time the client connects. The client cannot possibly change versions (i.e. upgrade) but continue to use the same export on the server.\n{quote}\n\nSorry I don't get this. If the MGS is restarted, all of its exports will be destroyed, so it's impossible for the clients to use the same export on the server.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "baaa2cb99bcab69da0eb4dcd88b64d9d181dde73",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-09-07 18:14:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64, CentOS release 5.8/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/f03528ce-f915-11e1-a1b8-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e58e76e297a6ebd85693f196e537bdbf955c325b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-08 17:23:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI think it is still possible to handle this mostly on the server side, but we also should fix the clients to reset their ocd_version field at reconnect time to avoid this problem in the future.\n\nWhat needs to happen is that the client version checks should be removed as in this patch.\n\nIn addition, the clients will need to continue to send the OBD_CONNECT_MNE_SWAB flag for a longer time than the servers are checking for it. After about 2.6.50, the servers can assume that clients no longer need swabbing, while the clients should continue to send MNE_SWAB until about 3.2.50 so that they can interoperate with older servers.  After that version the clients can stop sending MNE_SWAB as well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7d47d5b00b05c5c2d5edffb5edf9087e40e4bb55",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-10 16:59:59.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 2.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "eb4ed9dea3cc4f1c9313f73e4d449c20ccb1a593",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-10 17:59:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nThe patch could land as-is - the extra checking is not harmful, but it won't do anything useful either.\n\nIf the patch can be refreshed quickly, then that would be fine, but we can also deal with this at a later time (e.g. when the other code is being cleaned up for 2.6.50) if the refresh would cause a delay in landing this fix.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
